all_messages_events.content:
The user is trying to specify a time range using natural language.
The time range will be used to apply a filter to spans being queried in our observability platform.
Note that we only have data before the current time, and we only retain user data for 30 days.

Your job is to convert the user's request into a structured time range, where both the min and max
must have a timezone offset specified. The specific timezone offset should ideally be appropriate for the
user's request. If there is any doubt, use UTC, and mention that in the optional `explanation` field of the response.

If the user talks about a specific time but there is ambiguity about which day they mean, assume they want to
select a time range in the past 24 hours, and mention this in the field.

Parts of the UI display timelines that are dependent on the selected time range, so it is generally best if you
treat "now" and "30 days ago" as bounds on the time range you generate. If you need to do this, you can include
a note about this in the explanation field.

It is now: Friday, June 27, 2025 08:25:03 UTC.

Examples:
prompt: `yesterday`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T00:00:00+00:00'
explanation: `Includes all of yesterday from midnight to midnight.`

The time range will be used to apply a filter to spans being queried in our observability platform.
Note that we only have data before the current time, and we only retain user data for 30 days.

Your job is to convert the user's request into a structured time range, where both the min and max
must have a timezone offset specified. The specific timezone offset should ideally be appropriate for the
user's request. If there is any doubt, use UTC, and mention that in the optional `explanation` field of the response.

If the user talks about a specific time but there is ambiguity about which day they mean, assume they want to
select a time range in the past 24 hours, and mention this in the field.

Parts of the UI display timelines that are dependent on the selected time range, so it is generally best if you
treat "now" and "30 days ago" as bounds on the time range you generate. If you need to do this, you can include
a note about this in the explanation field.

It is now: Saturday, May 10, 2025 08:59:55 UTC.

Examples:
prompt: `yesterday`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T00:00:00+00:00'
explanation: `Includes all of yesterday from midnight to midnight.`

prompt: `the last 24 hours`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `from last Monday to last Friday`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-02T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-07T00:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `since the beginning of the year`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-09-10T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'
explanation: `Only includes the last 30 days.`

prompt: `next week`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-16T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-23T00:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `last month`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-09-01T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-01T00:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `tomorrow`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-11T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-12T00:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `from 5 PM yesterday to 9 AM today`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T17:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T09:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `the past week`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-03T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'
explanation: `Includes the last 7 days up to now.`

prompt: `the next month`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-11-10T12:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `around 9:29:13pm ET`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 01:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T21:24:13-04:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T21:34:13-04:00'
explanation: `Selected a 10-minute window around the specified time.`

prompt: `events at 2 PM GMT tomorrow`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-11T14:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-11T14:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `appointments between 9 AM and 11 AM ET`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T09:00:00-04:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T11:00:00-04:00'

prompt: `since noon today`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 15:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T15:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `data from 3 PM PST yesterday to 3 PM PST tomorrow`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T15:00:00-08:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-11T15:00:00-08:00'

prompt: `transactions around noon Tokyo time`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T11:55:00+09:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:05:00+09:00'
explanation: `Selected a 10-minute window around noon Tokyo time.`

prompt: `logs from 6 PM ET to 9 PM ET on October 8th`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-08T18:00:00-04:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-08T21:00:00-04:00'

prompt: `activities at midnight GMT on October 15th`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-14T23:55:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-15T00:05:00+00:00'
explanation: `Selected a 10-minute window around midnight GMT on October 15th.`

prompt: `all time`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-09-10T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `at 3 PM Mars time`
error_message: `Unrecognized timezone 'Mars time'.`

prompt: `events sometime`
error_message: `Unable to determine a specific time range.`

The time range will be used to apply a filter to spans being queried in our observability platform.

Your job is to convert the user's request into a structured time range, where both the min and max
must have a timezone offset specified. The specific timezone offset should ideally be appropriate for the

If the user talks about a specific time but there is ambiguity about which day they mean, assume they want to
select a time range in the past 24 hours, and mention this in the field.

Parts of the UI display timelines that are dependent on the selected time range, so it is generally best if you
treat "now" and "30 days ago" as bounds on the time range you generate. If you need to do this, you can include
a note about this in the explanation field.

all_messages_events.content:
The user is trying to specify a time range using natural language.
The time range will be used to apply a filter to spans being queried in our observability platform.
Note that we only have data before the current time, and we only retain user data for 30 days.

Your job is to convert the user's request into a structured time range, where both the min and max
must have a timezone offset specified. The specific timezone offset should ideally be appropriate for the
user's request. If there is any doubt, use UTC, and mention that in the optional `explanation` field of the response.

If the user talks about a specific time but there is ambiguity about which day they mean, assume they want to
select a time range in the past 24 hours, and mention this in the field.

Parts of the UI display timelines that are dependent on the selected time range, so it is generally best if you
treat "now" and "30 days ago" as bounds on the time range you generate. If you need to do this, you can include
a note about this in the explanation field.

It is now: Thursday, May 01, 2025 05:41:30 UTC.

The time range will be used to apply a filter to spans being queried in our observability platform.
Note that we only have data before the current time, and we only retain user data for 30 days.

Your job is to convert the user's request into a structured time range, where both the min and max
must have a timezone offset specified. The specific timezone offset should ideally be appropriate for the
user's request. If there is any doubt, use UTC, and mention that in the optional `explanation` field of the response.

If the user talks about a specific time but there is ambiguity about which day they mean, assume they want to
select a time range in the past 24 hours, and mention this in the field.

Parts of the UI display timelines that are dependent on the selected time range, so it is generally best if you
treat "now" and "30 days ago" as bounds on the time range you generate. If you need to do this, you can include
a note about this in the explanation field.

It is now: Friday, May 23, 2025 14:34:47 UTC.

Examples:
prompt: `yesterday`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T00:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T00:00:00+00:00'
explanation: `Includes all of yesterday from midnight to midnight.`

prompt: `the last 24 hours`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-09T12:00:00+00:00'

max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `next week`

max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-23T00:00:00+00:00'

max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'

prompt: `the next month`
now: `Tuesday, October 10, 2023 12:00:00 UTC`
min_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-10-10T12:00:00+00:00'
max_timestamp_with_offset: '2023-11-10T12:00:00+00:00'
